{"questionId":"27734","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Consider a quadrilateral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ABCD</mtext></math> such that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>AB</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>BC</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mtext>CD</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>DA</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>, as shown&nbsp;in the following diagram. Let <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mover><mtext>B</mtext><mo>^</mo></mover><mtext>C</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>β</mi><mo>=</mo><mtext>A</mtext><mover><mtext>D</mtext><mo>^</mo></mover><mtext>C</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/3b6a754e69cb43305300c2a81e6f6f510bf354a1.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the maximum area of the quadrilateral <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>ABCD</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to find the sum of two triangle areas using&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>a</mi><mi>b</mi><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>C</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Do not award this <em><strong>M1</strong></em> if the triangle is assumed to be right angled.</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>Area</mtext><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mn>8</mn></mfenced><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>α</mi><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mfenced><mn>48</mn></mfenced><mi>sin</mi><mo> </mo><mi>β</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &n